          <td valign="top">

<span class="txth1">conomode.vim : Vi-style editing for the command line</span> 

<br>
<br>

<!-- karma table -->
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="1" bordercolor="#000066">
<tr>
  <td class="lightbg"><b>&nbsp;script karma&nbsp;</b></td>
  <td>
    Rating <b>2/2</b>,
    Downloaded by 239  </td>
  <td class="lightbg">
  <b>&nbsp;Comments, bugs, improvements&nbsp;</b>
  </td>
  <td>
    <a href="http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/Script:2388">Vim wiki</a>
  </td>  
</tr>
</table>
<p>

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
<tr><td class="prompt">created by</td></tr>
<tr><td><a href="/account/profile.php?user_id=8357">Andy Wokula</a></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">script type</td></tr>
<tr><td>utility</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">description</td></tr>
<tr><td>Implements a kind of Normal mode ( &quot;Cmdline-Normal mode&quot; ) on top of the Command line.&nbsp;&nbsp;Purpose is similar to the cmdline-window (q:), but navigation and editing can be done in-place.&nbsp;&nbsp;Of course the cmdline-window is much more powerful.<br><br>- enter with c_&lt;F4&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; (press &lt;F4&gt; while in Command-line mode)<br>- mode indicator is a colon &quot;:&quot;, moved along with the cursor, hiding the char under it<br>- quit to Cmdline-mode with &lt;Esc&gt;, o, O, &quot;:&quot; or any unmapped key (which then executes or inserts itself), or wait 60 seconds.<br><br>Features So Far:<br>- Motions: h l w b e W B E 0 ^ $ f{char} F{char} ; ,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;also in Operator pending mode<br>- More Motions: j k<br>- Operators: d y c&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;these write to the unnamed register; c prompts for input()<br>- Insert: I i a A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; these commands prompt for input()<br>- Shortcuts: yy D x X s C dd&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;yy -&gt; 0y$, D -&gt; d$, x -&gt; dl, X -&gt; dh, s -&gt; cl, C -&gt; c$, dd -&gt; 0d$<br>- Simple Changes: r{char} ~<br>- Putting: P p&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;put the unnamed register<br>- Repeating: .&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;repeatable commands: d r c ~ I i a A<br>- Macros: q @&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; q starts[/stops] recording, @ executes, no register involved<br>- Mode Switching: &lt;Esc&gt; o O - back to Cmdline, &lt;CR&gt; - execute Cmdline<br>- Undo: u U&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; redo with &quot;U&quot; (to keep c_CTRL-R working); undo information survives mode switching; undo is unlimited<br>- Count: can be given for most commands<br>- Misc: &lt;C-L&gt; - redraw the Cmdline<br><br>Notes:<br>- the mode indicator may make UTF-8 characters look garbled; press Ctrl-L to redraw the Cmdline<br><br>Have fun!</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">install details</td></tr>
<tr><td>:source conomode.vim<br><br>Can be used as a plugin, but:<br>Note: Vim7.3 is recommended, older Vims are likely to crash due to a bug in getcmdline()<br><br>The plugin defines a lot of mappings for Cmdline-mode, but these are local to the script -- so except for &lt;F4&gt; (and &lt;C-X&gt; for internal use), there cannot be a conflict with other mappings.<br><br><br>Hint:<br>to autoload the plugin when pressing &lt;F4&gt; the first time, you can create a &quot;macros&quot; folder, put the script file there and add the following code to your vimrc:<br><br>&quot; vimrc:<br>cmap &lt;F4&gt; &lt;C-R&gt;=&lt;sid&gt;LoadConoMode()&lt;CR&gt;&lt;F4&gt;<br><br>func! &lt;sid&gt;LoadConoMode()<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;cunmap &lt;F4&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;verbose runtime macros/conomode.vim<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;redraw<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return &quot;&quot;<br>endfunc<br><br>2010 Aug 21</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
</table>

